Joram begat Uzziah, and Uzziah begat Jotham, and Jotham begat Ahaz,
His son Jotham, Jotham fathered Ahaz, and Ahaz fathered Hezekiah.
Hezekiah was the father of Manasseh, and Manasseh was the father of Amon, and Amon was the father of Josiah.
And Josiah was the father of Jechoniah and his brothers. At that time, the Jewish people were taken captive to Babylon.
Then the family line continued through Jeconiah, the father of Shealtiel, and Shealtiel was the father of Zerubbabel.
Zerrubbabel is the father of Abiud. Abiud is the father of Eliakim. Eliakim is the father of Ezra.
Ashur was the father of Shelemiah, and Shelemiah was the father of Jehu, and Jehu was the father of Azariah.
And Eleazar begat Phares, and Phares begat Esrom, and Esrom begat Aram.
Jacob was the father of Joseph. Joseph was the husband of Mary. And Mary gave birth to Jesus, who is called the Messiah.
So there were ten generations from Adam to Noah, ten from Noah to Abraham, ten from Abraham to David, ten from David to the tribe of Judah, and ten from the tribe of Judah to Jesus Christ, who is called the Messiah.
This is how the birth of Jesus Christ came about: His mother Mary was pledged to be married to Joseph, but before they came together, she was found to be with child through the Holy Spirit.
Her husband, Joseph, was a righteous man. He did not want to expose her publicly. So, he planned to divorce her quietly.
But while Joseph was considering this, an angel of the Lord appeared to him in a dream and said, "Joseph son of David, do not be afraid to take Mary as your wife, for the child conceived in her is from the Holy Spirit.
You will bear a son. You must name him Jesus, for he will save his people from their sins.
All this happened so that what the Lord had said would come true, as he had announced through the prophet,
"The virgin will conceive and give birth to a son, and they will call him Immanuel," which means "God with us." (Isaiah 7:14)
Joseph woke up. He did as the angel of the Lord commanded him. He took Mary into his home as his wife.
But he had no union with her until she gave birth to a son, and he gave him the name Jesus.
The Visit of the Wise Men to Jesus
Jesus was born in Bethlehem in Judea. This happened while Herod was king of Judea. After the birth of Jesus, wise men from the East came to Jerusalem.
So they said to him, “Where is the one who has been born king of the Jews? For we saw his star at its rising and have come to worship him.”
When King Herod heard this, he was greatly disturbed, as was the whole population of Jerusalem.
Then Herod summoned the wise men secretly and ascertained from them the time of the star’s appearance.
"In Bethlehem in Judah," they answered. "This is what the prophet wrote. He said,
"But you, Bethlehem Ephrathah, though you are small among the clans of Judah, yet out of you will come for me one who will be ruler over Israel, whose origins are from of old, from ancient times." (Micah 5:2)
Then Herod called the magi secretly and found out from them the exact time the star had appeared.
Send them to Bethlehem, saying, "Go and search carefully for the child. When you have found him, bring me word, so that I too may go and pay him homage."
And when the wise men had heard the king, they departed; and, lo, the star, which they saw in the east, went before them, till it came and stood over where the young child was.
When they saw the star, they were filled with joy.
The wise men went to the house. There they saw the child with his mother Mary. They knelt down and worshiped him. Then they opened their treasures. They gave him gold, frankincense, and myrrh.
But God warned them in a dream not to return to Herod. So they returned to their country by another route. The flight of Jesus' family into Egypt.
When the Magi had departed, behold, the angel of the Lord appeared to Joseph in a dream and said, "Arise, take the child and his mother, and flee to Egypt, and remain there until I tell you, for Herod is about to seek the child to destroy him."
Joseph arose. During the night, he departed for Egypt with the child and his mother Mary.
They remained there until the death of King Herod, that what was spoken by the Lord through the prophets might be fulfilled: "Out of Egypt I called my son" (Hosea 11:1).
Herod realized that the wise men had deceived him. He was furious and issued orders regarding Bethlehem and its surroundings. All boys two years old and under had to be killed. This corresponded to the time when the wise men had seen the star.
Thus were fulfilled the words of the prophet Jeremiah, which he spake:
"A voice is heard in Ramah, a voice of weeping and great mourning. Rachel is weeping for her children; she refuses to be comforted, because they are no more." (Jeremiah 31:15) Jesus' family returns to Nazareth.
After Herod was dead, behold, an angel of the Lord appeared to Joseph in a dream, while he was still in Egypt.
The angel said, "Arise, take the child and his mother, and go to the land of Israel, for those who sought the child's life are dead."
So Joseph got up, took the child and his mother and left during the night for Egypt.
But when he heard that Archelaus was reigning over Judea in place of his father Herod, he was afraid to go there. And after being warned in a dream, he went to the lands of Galilee instead.
So he went and lived in a town called Nazareth, so that what had been spoken through the prophets might be fulfilled: "He will be called a Nazarene."
John the Baptist prepares the way.
In those days John the Baptist came, preaching in the wilderness of Judea.
He said, "Repent from your sins! The kingdom of heaven is near."
John is the one of whom the prophet Isaiah spoke, saying, "A voice cries out in the wilderness: 'Prepare the way of the Lord, make straight in the desert a road for our God.'" (Isaiah 40:3)
John's clothes were made of camel's hair, and he wore a leather belt around his waist. His food was locusts and wild honey.
People went out to him from Jerusalem, and from all Judea, and from all the region around the Jordan.
When they confessed their sins, John baptized them in the Jordan River.
John saw many Pharisees and Sadducees coming to where he was baptizing, and he said to them, "You brood of vipers! Who warned you to flee from the wrath to come?
Bear fruit worthy of repentance for your sins.
Do not think that you will enter the kingdom of heaven by saying, 'We are descendants of Abraham.' I tell you, many will come from east and west and recline at table with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven, while the sons of the kingdom will be thrown into the outer darkness.
The axe is already lying at the roots of the trees. All trees that do not bear good fruit will be cut down. They will be thrown into the fire.
"I baptize you with water, calling on you to repent. But after me comes one who is more powerful than I, and I am not fit to untie the thong of his sandals. He will baptize you with the Holy Spirit and fire."
His pitchfork in hand to clear the hay from his barn. He gathers his wheat into the granary. But the chaff he burns in the inextinguishable fire." The Baptism of Jesus
Jesus came from Galilee to the Jordan River to be baptized by John.
But John tried to prevent him, saying to Jesus, "I need to be baptized by you, why are you coming to me?"
Jesus answered, "Let it be so now; it is proper for us to do this to fulfill all righteousness." Then John consented.
As soon as Jesus was baptized, he came up out of the water. At that moment, the heavens opened, and he saw the Spirit of God descending like a dove and lighting on him.
A voice from heaven said, "This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased."
Jesus is tempted.
The Spirit led Jesus into the wilderness, where he was tempted by the devil.
After forty days and forty nights of fasting, Jesus was hungry.
The tempter came to him and said, "If you are the Son of God, command that these stones become loaves of bread."
Jesus answered, "It is written, 'Man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that comes from the mouth of God.'" (Deuteronomy 8:3)
So he took him to Jerusalem and set him on the pinnacle of the temple.
So he said to him, "If you are the Son of God, throw yourself down, for it is written: 'He will command his angels concerning you, to guard you,' and 'On their hands they will bear you up, so that you will not dash your foot against a stone'" (Psalm 91:11-12).
Jesus answered him, "It is written, 'You shall not put the Lord your God to the test'" (Deuteronomy 6:16).
Finally, the devil took Jesus to a very high mountain. He showed him all the kingdoms of the world and their glory.
"If you bow down to me and worship me," he said, "I will give you all this."
Then Jesus said to him, "Away with you, Satan! For it is written, 'You shall worship the Lord your God and him only shall you serve.'" (Deuteronomy 6:13)
Then the devil left Jesus, and angels came and attended to him. Jesus began to preach.
When Jesus heard that John had been put in prison, he withdrew to Galilee.
Jesus left Nazareth and went to live in Capernaum, which was by the lake in the region of Zebulun and Naphtali.
In this way, the prophecy of the prophet Isaiah was fulfilled. He had said:
Land of Zebulun! Land of Naphtali! Galilee, where the Gentiles live! The land along the Mediterranean Sea! The region east of the Jordan River!
"The people walking in darkness will see a great light. For those living in a land of deep darkness, a light will shine on them." (Isaiah 9:1, 2)
From that time Jesus began to preach, saying, "Repent, for the kingdom of heaven is at hand." Jesus chooses the first disciples.
One day, Jesus was walking by the Sea of Galilee. There he saw two brothers, Simon Peter and his brother Andrew. They were casting a net into the lake, for they were fishermen.
Jesus said, "Come, follow me, and I will make you fishers of men."
So they left their nets and followed him immediately.
Going on from there, he saw two other brothers, James the son of Zebedee and John his brother, in a boat with their father Zebedee, mending their nets. And he called them.
Immediately they left the boat and their father and followed Jesus. Jesus healed the sick people.
Jesus went throughout Galilee, teaching in their synagogues, preaching the good news of the Kingdom of God, and healing every disease and every sickness among the people.
His fame spread throughout Syria, and people brought to him all who were sick with various diseases. Some were suffering from severe pains, some were possessed by demons, some were epileptics, and some were paralyzed. Jesus healed them all.
Large crowds followed him. Some people came from Galilee, and from the Decapolis, and from Jerusalem and Judea. Others came from the region across the Jordan.
Jesus grants blessings.
Jesus saw the crowds, went up the mountain, and sat down. His disciples came to him.
Then he began to teach them, saying:
Blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they will be filled.
Blessed are those who mourn, for they will be comforted.
Blessed are the humble, for they shall inherit the earth.
Blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they will be filled.
Blessed are the merciful, for they shall obtain mercy.
Blessed are the pure in heart, for they shall see God.
Blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall be called sons of God.
Blessed are those who are persecuted for the sake of righteousness, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.
"Blessed are you when people insult you, persecute you and falsely say all kinds of evil against you because of me."
Rejoice and be glad, for your reward is great in heaven. So they also persecuted the prophets who were before you. "You are the salt of the earth and the light of the world."
You are the salt of the earth. But what if the salt loses its saltiness? How can it become salty again? It is no longer good for anything. It will be thrown out. People will trample it underfoot.
You are the light of the world. A city built on a hill cannot be hidden.
Likewise, people don't light a lamp and put it under a bushel basket, but on a stand, and it gives light to everyone in the house.
In the same way, let your light shine before others, so that they may see your good works and give glory to your Father in heaven. Jesus gives the full meaning of the law.
Do not think that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I have not come to abolish them but to fulfill them.
What I am about to tell you is true. Heaven and earth will disappear before the smallest letter of the law disappears. Not even the smallest stroke of a pen will disappear from the law until everything is accomplished.
Do not break even the smallest commandment. Do not teach others to break it either. For if you do, you will be called the least in the kingdom of heaven. But if you keep these commandments and teach them, you will be called great in the kingdom of heaven.
This is what I tell you: You must be more righteous than the Pharisees and the teachers of the law. If you are not, you will never enter the kingdom of heaven. Murder.
You have heard that it was said to those of ancient times, 'You shall not murder' (Exodus 20:13). Whoever murders will be liable to judgment.
But this is what I tell you: Do not be angry with your brother. Whoever is angry with his brother will be subject to judgment. And whoever says to his brother, 'Raca,' will be handed over to the Sanhedrin. But whoever says, 'You fool,' will be subject to hellfire.
"If your gift is on the altar and you remember that your brother has something against you"
Leave your gift before the altar and go first be reconciled with your brother; then come and present your gift.
"If anyone has a claim against you, go to him quickly while you are still together and settle the matter, or he may drag you into court and the judge may hand you over to the officer, and you may be thrown into prison."
What I'm about to tell you is true. You're not leaving until you pay the last penny! Whore.
You have heard that it was said, "Do not commit adultery." (Exodus 20:14)
But I tell you that anyone who looks at a woman to lust after her has already committed adultery with her in his heart.
If your right eye causes you to sin, gouge it out and throw it away. It is better for you to lose one eye than to have your whole body thrown into hell.
"If your hand causes you to sin, cut it off; it is better for you to enter life maimed than to have two hands and go to hell, where the fire will never be put out. Mark 9:43"
It is written: "When a man divorces his wife, he must give her a certificate of divorce." (Deuteronomy 24:1)
But I tell you: Whoever divorces his wife makes her an adulteress, and whoever marries a divorced woman commits adultery. A man can divorce his wife only if she has been unfaithful to him. Oath.
Once again, you have heard what was said to your people long ago: "Do not break the covenant that you made with the Lord. Keep the oaths you swore to him."
But this I say to you: Make no such promises at all. Make them not in the name of heaven. For that is God's throne.
Do not make them in the name of the Earth. It is the foothold of God's feet. Nor shall you make them in the name of Jerusalem. It is the city of the great King.
Do not take your oaths seriously, lest you incur sin and enmity. Is it not just a single strand of hair that you can make white or black?
Let "yes" mean "yes" and "no" mean "no." Anything more comes from the devil. Be kind to others.
You have heard that it was said, 'An eye for an eye and a tooth for a tooth.' (Exodus 21:24; Leviticus 24:20; Deuteronomy 19:21)
But I tell you, do not resist an evil person. If anyone slaps you on the right cheek, turn to them the other cheek also.
If anyone wants to sue you and take your tunic, let him have your cloak as well.
If someone forces you to walk a mile, walk two miles with him.
Give to those who ask of you. Do not turn away from those who want to borrow from you. Love your enemies.
You have heard that it was said, 'Love your neighbor and hate your enemy.' (Leviticus 19:18)
But I say to you: Love your enemies, and pray for those who persecute you.
So you shall be perfect, as your heavenly Father is perfect. For he makes his sun rise on the evil and on the good, and sends rain on the just and on the unjust.
If you love those who love you, what reward will you get? Even tax collectors do the same.
If you only greet your brothers, what more are you doing than others? Even those who do not fear God do that.
Therefore you are to be perfect, as your heavenly Father is perfect.
Giving to the needy
Beware of doing good deeds in front of others. Do not do them to be seen by others. If you do, your Father who is in heaven will not reward you.
"When you give to the needy, do not announce it with trumpets, as the hypocrites do in the synagogues and on the streets, to be seen by men. I tell you the truth, they have received their reward in full."
When you give to the needy, do not let your left hand know what your right hand is doing.
Then your giving will be in secret. Your Father who sees in secret will reward you. Prayer
When you pray, do not be like the hypocrites who love to pray standing in the synagogues and on the street corners to be seen by people. Truly I tell you, they have already received their reward.
When you pray, go into your rooms, close the doors, and pray to your Father who is in secret. He will reward you. For your Father sees in secret.
When you pray, do not be like the hypocrites, who love to pray standing in the synagogues and on the street corners to be seen by people. Truly I tell you, they have already received their reward.
Do not be like them. Your father knows what you need even before you ask him.
"Our Father in heaven, hallowed be your name.
Your kingdom come. Your will be done, on earth as it is in heaven.
Give us this day our daily bread.
Forgive us our sins, as we also forgive those who sin against us.
"Protect us from falling into sin when we are tempted. Save us from the evil one."
Forgive people if they wrong you, for your Father in heaven will also forgive you.
But if you do not forgive others their trespasses, neither will your Father forgive you your trespasses. Matthew 6:15
When you fast, do not look gloomy like the hypocrites who disfigure their faces to show others that they are fasting. Truly I tell you, they have received their reward in full.
But when you fast, anoint your head and wash your face.
Then your Father, who sees what is done in secret, will reward you. For your Father sees what is done in secret. When you fast, do not look somber as the hypocrites do, for they disfigure their faces to show others they are fasting. Truly I tell you, they have received their reward in full. But when you fast, put oil on your face and wash your face, so that it will not be obvious to others that you are fasting, but only to your Father, who is unseen; and your Father, who sees what is done in secret, will reward you.
Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth, where moths and vermin destroy, and where thieves break in and steal.
But make yourselves treasures in heaven, where neither moth nor rust consumes, and where neither thieves break in nor thieves steal.
Your heart will be where your treasure is.
The eye is like a lamp for the body. So, if your eye is clear, your whole body will be full of light.
But suppose your eyes were bad. Then your whole body would be full of darkness. If the light within you is darkness, how great is that darkness!
No one can serve two masters at the same time. He will hate one and love the other. Or he will be devoted to one and despise the other. You cannot serve God and money at the same time. Do not be anxious.
I tell you, do not worry about your life, what you will eat or drink; or about your body, what you will wear. Is not life more than food, and the body more than clothing?
"Look at the birds of the air; they do not sow or reap or store away in barns, and yet your heavenly Father feeds them. Are you not much more valuable than they?"
Can you add even an hour to your life by worrying?
And why do you worry about clothing? Look at the lilies of the field, how they grow; they neither toil nor spin.
But I tell you that not even Solomon in all his glory was clothed like one of these.
"If God does not clothe the grass of the field, which is here today and tomorrow is thrown into the oven, will He not much more clothe you, O you of little faith?"
Therefore do not worry, saying, "What will we eat?" or "What will we drink?" or "What will we wear?"
"All these things the pagans seek. Your heavenly Father knows that you need them."
But seek first the kingdom of God and His righteousness, and all these things shall be added to you.
Therefore do not worry about tomorrow, for tomorrow will worry about itself. Each day has enough trouble of its own.
Be fair when you judge others.
Do not judge, so that you may not be judged.
You will be judged as you judge others. You will be measured as you measure others.
You see a speck of sawdust in your friend's eye, but you do not notice the log in your own eye.
How can you tell your friend: "Let me remove the splinter from your eye," when there's a splinter in your own eye?
You hypocrite, first take the plank out of your own eye, and then you will see clearly to remove the speck from your brother's eye.
Do not give what is holy to the dogs, nor cast your pearls before swine, lest they trample them under their feet, and turn and tear you in pieces. Ask, and it will be given to you; seek, and you will find; knock, and it will be opened to you.
