Then I will declare to them, 'I never knew you; depart from me, you evildoers!' Builders of wisdom and fools.
Therefore, everyone who hears these words of mine and acts on them will be like a wise man who built his house on the rock.
It rains. The water rises. The wind blows and strikes that house. But it doesn't fall. It's built on rock.
But everyone who hears these words of mine and does not put them into practice is like a foolish man who built his house on sand.
It rains. The water rises. The wind blows and hits that house. It falls with a loud crash.
Jesus finished saying all these things, and the crowds were amazed at his teaching.
He taught with authority, and not as their scribes.
Jesus heals a man with a skin disease.
Jesus came down from the mountain, and a large crowd followed him.
A man with a skin disease came to him and knelt down before Jesus, saying, "Lord, if you choose, you can make me clean."
Jesus reached out his hand and touched the man. He said, "I am willing to do this; be made clean!" Immediately the man was cleansed of his leprosy.
Then Jesus answered and said to him, "See that you tell no one; but go your way, show yourself to the priest, and offer the gift that Moses commanded, as a testimony to them." The faith of the Roman centurion.
When Jesus came to Capernaum, a Roman centurion approached him and pleaded for his help.
So he said, "Sir, your servant is lying at home paralyzed, in great pain and unable to move."
Jesus said, "I will go and heal him."
The captain answered, "Sir, I am not worthy that you should come under my roof, but just say the word, and my servant will be healed."
I myself am a man in authority. I have soldiers who obey my commands. I say to this one, 'Go,' and he goes. I say to that one, 'Come,' and he comes. I say to my servant, 'Do this,' and he does it."
When Jesus heard this, he marveled and said to those who followed him, "Truly, I tell you, I have not found anyone in Israel with such great faith."
I tell you, many will come from east and west and recline at table with Abraham, Isaac and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven.
But those who think they belong to the kingdom will be thrown outside, into the darkness, where there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.
Then Jesus said to the centurion, "Go, as you have believed, so let it be done to you." And his servant was healed in that very hour.
When Jesus came into Peter's house, he saw Peter's mother-in-law lying in bed with a fever.
So Jesus took her by the hand, and the fever left her. And she rose and began to serve him.
When evening came, many who had demons were brought to him, and he drove out the spirits with a word and healed all the sick.
He did this to fulfill what the prophet Isaiah had said: "He carried our sicknesses and our pains; yet we regarded him as punished, struck by God, and humiliated" (Isaiah 53:4). Following Jesus requires sacrifice.
Seeing the crowds around him, Jesus instructed his disciples to cross to the other side of the Sea of Galilee.
Then one of the scribes came to him and said to him, "Teacher, I will follow you wherever you go."
Jesus answered, "Foxes have holes, and birds of the sky have nests, but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head."
Then another of his disciples said to him, "Lord, let me first go and bury my father."
But Jesus said to him, "Follow Me. Let the dead bury their own dead." Jesus calms the storm.
Jesus got into a boat, and his disciples followed him.
Suddenly, a terrible storm arose on the lake. The waves were overtaking the boat. But Jesus was sleeping.
Then the disciples woke him up, saying, "Teacher, save us! We are perishing!"
He answered them, "How little faith you have! Why are you so afraid?" Then he got up and rebuked the winds and the waves, and it was completely calm.
The disciples were amazed and asked, "What kind of man is this? Even the winds and the sea obey him!" Jesus heals two demon-possessed men.
Jesus arrived on the other side of the lake, in the region of the Gadarenes. He met two men possessed by demons, coming out of the tombs. The men were so violent that no one could pass by.
"Son of God, what do you want with us?" they cried. "Have you come to punish us before our time of judgment?"
Not far away, there was a large herd of pigs grazing.
The demons begged Jesus, "If you drive us out, send us into the herd of pigs."
Then Jesus said to them, "Go." And the demons came out of the men and entered the pigs. And the herd rushed down the steep slope into the lake and drowned.
So the swineherds fled and spread the news in the town and in the countryside about everything that had happened, particularly about the men who had been possessed by demons.
So the whole city came out to meet Jesus. And when they saw him, they begged him to leave their region.
Jesus heals a man who cannot walk.
Jesus got into a boat and crossed over to the other side of the lake to his hometown.
Some men came, carrying a paralyzed man on a mat. When Jesus saw their faith, he said to the paralyzed man, "Take heart, son; your sins are forgiven."
Then some of the scribes in their hearts said, "This man is blaspheming!"
Jesus knew their thoughts and said to them, "Why do you entertain evil thoughts in your hearts?"
Is it easier to say, "Your sins are forgiven"? Or to say, "Get up and walk"?
"I want you to know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins." Then he said to the paralyzed man, "Get up, take your mat, and go to your house."
The man stood up and went home.
When the crowd saw this, they were filled with awe, and they praised God, who had given such authority to human beings. (Gospel of Matthew 9:8)
As Jesus was walking along, he saw a man called Matthew sitting at the tax collector’s booth. “Follow me,” he told him. And Matthew got up and followed him.
Later, Jesus was dining at Matthew's house with many tax collectors and sinners. They ate with Jesus and his disciples.
When the Pharisees saw this, they asked his disciples, "Why does your teacher eat with tax collectors and sinners?"
