The Farmer's Tale
On that day, Jesus went out of the house and sat by the Sea of Galilee.
A large crowd gathered around him. So he got into a boat. He sat in it, and all the people stood on the shore.
Then he proceeded to tell them many things, using parables. He said: "A farmer went out to sow his seed.
He scattered the seeds on the ground. Some fell on the path. Birds came and ate them.
Some seeds fell on rocky places, where there was little soil. The plants grew quickly, because the soil was not deep.
When the sun rose, it scorched the plants. They withered because they had no roots.
Other seeds fell among the thorns. The thorns grew up and choked the plants.
Other seeds fell on good soil, grew, and produced a hundredfold, sixtyfold, and thirtyfold.
"He who has ears to hear, let him hear."
His disciples came to him and asked, "Why do you speak to the people in parables?"
He answered them, "To you it has been given to know the secrets of the kingdom of heaven, but to them it has not been given."
Anyone who has this kind of knowledge will be given more. In fact, they will have too much. If no one has this kind of knowledge, even the little they have will be taken away.
This is why I use stories when I talk to people. I say, "They look, but they don't really see. They listen, but they don't really hear or understand."
In them is fulfilled the prophecy of Isaiah, which says: "You will indeed hear, but never understand; you will indeed see, but never perceive."
"The hearts of these people have become callous; their ears are unable to hear. They have closed their eyes, otherwise they would see with their eyes, hear with their ears, understand with their hearts, and turn to the Lord for healing." (Isaiah 6:9-10)
But blessed are your eyes, for they see. And blessed are your ears, for they hear.
What I am about to tell you is the truth. Many prophets and righteous people wanted to see what you see, but they didn't see it. They wanted to hear what you hear, but they didn't hear it.
Listen! This is the meaning of the farmer's story.
People hear the message of the kingdom but do not understand it. Then the evil one comes and steals what was sown in their hearts. These people are like the seed that was sown on the path.
"But those that fell on the rocky places are those who, when they hear the word, receive it with joy immediately."
But they have no roots, so they do not last long. They quickly fall away from the faith when tribulation or persecution arises because of the message.
And others fell among the thorns. These are the ones who hear the message, but then the worries of daily life and the deceptive promise of wealth choke them. They prevent them from bearing fruit.
But others received the seed that fell on good soil. These are the ones who hear the message and understand it. They produce a crop that is a hundred times, sixty times, or thirty times more than what was sown. "The Parable of the Weeds"
