A large crowd came to him, bringing with them the lame, the blind, the crippled, those who cannot speak, and many others. They laid them at his feet, and he healed them.
So the people were amazed. Those who could not speak were speaking, the lame were walking, the blind were seeing. And the people praised the God of Israel.
Then Jesus called his disciples to him and said to them, "I have compassion on these people; they have been with me for three days now and have nothing to eat. I do not want to send them away hungry, or they may collapse on the way home."
His disciples answered him, "There is nothing here but five loaves and two fish." They said, "What are these among so many?"
Jesus asked, "How many loaves do you have?" They answered, "Seven, and a few small fish."
Jesus commanded the multitudes to sit down on the ground.
Then he took the seven loaves and the fish, and having given thanks, he broke them and gave them to the disciples, and the disciples gave them to the people.
So they all ate and were satisfied. Then the disciples picked up seven basketfuls of broken pieces that were left over.
The number of men who ate was 4000. Women and children also ate.
After Jesus had dismissed the crowds, he got into the boat and came to the region of Magadan.
Jesus is asked for a sign.
The Pharisees and Sadducees came to test Jesus. They asked him to show them a sign from heaven.
He answered, "In the evening you look at the sky and say, 'The weather will be good. The sky is red.'"
In the morning you say, "There will be a storm today. The sky is red and cloudy." You know the meaning of what you see in the sky. But you cannot understand the signs of what is happening now.
"An evil and adulterous generation seeks for a sign, but no sign will be given to it except the sign of Jonah." And he left them and went away. "The leaven of the Pharisees and the Sadducees"
The disciples crossed to the other side of the sea, and they forgot to bring bread.
Then Jesus said to them, "Beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees."
The pupils talked about this among themselves and said, "He must be saying this because we didn't bring any bread."
Jesus knew their discussion, and said to them, "Why do you discuss among yourselves about having no bread? Do you still not perceive and understand? Are your hearts hardened?"
Don't you understand yet? Don't you remember the five loaves for the five thousand? Don't you remember how many baskets of fragments you gathered?
"Do you not remember the seven loaves that were enough for four thousand men? Or how many baskets full of fragments did you take up?"
How can you not understand? I was not talking to you about bread. But beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees.
Then the disciples understood that Jesus was not warning them about the leaven of bread, but about the teaching of the Pharisees and Sadducees. Peter said, "You are the Christ."
Jesus went to the region of Caesarea Philippi. There he asked his disciples, "Who do people say I am?"
They answered, "Some say it is John the Baptist. Others say it is Elijah. Still others say it is Jeremiah or one of the prophets."
But he asked, "What about you? Who do you say that I am?"
Simon Peter answered, "You are the Christ, the Son of the living God."
Jesus answered, "Blessed are you, Simon son of Jonah! For flesh and blood has not revealed this to you, but my Father who is in heaven."
This is what I tell you: You are Peter, and on this rock I will build my church, and the gates of hell will not overcome it.
I will give you the keys of the kingdom of heaven. Whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven, and whatever you loose on earth will be loosed in heaven.
So Jesus instructed his disciples not to tell anyone that he was the Messiah, Jesus. Jesus speaks of his upcoming death.
From that time Jesus began to show his disciples that he must go to Jerusalem and suffer many things from the elders and chief priests and scribes, and be killed, and on the third day be raised.
Peter took Jesus aside and began to rebuke him, saying, "Far be it from you, Lord! This must never happen to you!"
Then Jesus turned and said to Peter, "Get behind me, Satan! You are a stumbling block to me; for you are not setting your mind on the things of God, but on the things of man."
Then Jesus said to his disciples, "If anyone would come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross and follow me."
"If anyone would save his life, he will lose it; and whoever loses his life for my sake will find it."
What good is it to gain the whole world and lose one's soul? Or what can anyone give in exchange for their soul?
The Son of Man will come in his Father's glory, with his angels, and then he will reward each according to his works.
What I am about to tell you is true. Some who are standing here will not taste death before they see the Son of Man coming in his kingdom.
The appearance of Jesus was transformed.
Six days later, Jesus took Peter, James, and John, the brother of James, and led them up a high mountain by themselves.
There before them, his appearance was transformed. His face shone like the sun, and his clothes became as white as light.
At that moment, Moses and Elijah appeared before them. Moses and Elijah were speaking with Jesus.
Then Peter said to Jesus, "Lord, it is good that we are here. If you wish, let us make three tents: one for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah."
While Peter was still speaking, a bright cloud enveloped them. And a voice from the cloud said, "This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased. Listen to him."
When the disciples heard this, they were terrified and fell on their faces to the ground.
But Jesus came and touched them, saying, "Arise, and do not be afraid."
When they looked up, they saw no one but Jesus.
They came down from the mountain. And as they were coming down, Jesus commanded them, "Tell no one what you have seen." "Until the Son of Man has risen from the dead," he said to them.
So the disciples asked him, "Why do the scribes say that Elijah must come first?"
Jesus replied, "That is true. Elijah is to come and restore all things.
But I tell you, Elijah has already come, and they did not recognize him, but did to him whatever they pleased. So also will the Son of Man suffer at their hands.
Then the disciples understood that Jesus was speaking to them about John the Baptist. Jesus heals a boy possessed by a demon.
As they approached the crowd, a man came up to him and knelt before him.
"My lord," he said, "have mercy on my son. He shudders violently and suffers greatly. He often falls into the fire or into the water.
I brought him to your disciples, and they could not heal him."
"You brood of vipers! How long shall I be with you? How long shall I bear with you?" Jesus answered. "Bring the boy here to me."
Jesus commanded the demon to come out of the boy, and it did. The boy was healed at that moment.
Then the disciples came to Jesus in private and asked, "Why couldn't we drive it out?"
He answered them, "Because your faith is so small. I tell you the truth, if you have faith as small as a mustard seed, you can say to this mountain, 'Move from here to there' and it will move. Nothing will be impossible for you."
